Failure Taxonomy

Overview

The Intent Preservation Failure Taxonomy documents recurring patterns observed during the evaluation of large language models in the Intent Preservation Benchmark.

Rather than treating every error as an isolated mistake, this taxonomy organizes failures into recurring categories that describe how language models alter, omit, or distort human intent during complex information transformation.

The taxonomy is derived from the initial 20-case benchmark and will continue evolving as additional benchmark cases and language models are evaluated.



Information Omission

Definition

Clinically relevant information from the original documentation is missing from the generated output.

Examples

Missing medications
Missing follow-up appointments
Missing discharge instructions
Missing warning signs

Observed Benchmark Examples

Future benchmark releases will include representative examples of omitted medications, follow-up recommendations, and discharge instructions observed across evaluated cases.

Potential Impact

Incomplete communication may prevent patients or downstream providers from receiving important clinical information.



Unsupported Assumptions

Definition

The model introduces information that was not supported by the original documentation while remaining superficially plausible.

Observed Benchmark Examples

Case 003

The model introduced additional warning symptoms that were not documented in the original discharge summary.

Case 004

The model generated new warning instructions while preserving the overall treatment pathway.

Case 006

The model added subjective recovery language that was never stated in the clinician's documentation.

Potential Impact

Users may incorrectly assume that unsupported information originated from the clinician.



Hallucinated Clinical Information

Definition

The model generates new clinical details that were never present in the original documentation.

Observed Benchmark Examples

Examples observed during the benchmark include unsupported warning symptoms, fabricated recovery expectations, and additional clinical guidance not found in the source documentation.

Potential Impact

Hallucinated information may distort patient understanding and reduce confidence in AI-generated documentation.


Medication Inconsistencies

Definition

Medication information changes during information transformation.

Examples

Missing medications
Incorrect medication status
Altered medication instructions
Modified dosage information

Observed Benchmark Examples

As the benchmark expands, future versions will document recurring medication-related failure patterns identified across benchmark cases.

Potential Impact

Medication inconsistencies represent one of the highest-risk failure categories because they may directly influence patient care.



Clinical Meaning Drift

Definition

The generated response remains fluent while subtly changing the clinician's intended meaning.

Observed Benchmark Examples

Case 003

The model overstated oxygen recovery beyond what was documented.

Case 004

Measured clinical improvement became a broader claim of normalized breathing.

Case 005

The model reduced important nuance surrounding ongoing dysphagia management while preserving the overall narrative.

Potential Impact

Meaning drift is difficult to detect because the generated response appears reasonable while communicating something different from the original documentation.



Logical Reasoning Failures

Definition

The generated response contains conclusions or reasoning that are not fully supported by the source documentation.

Observed Benchmark Examples

Several benchmark cases demonstrated logically plausible conclusions that extended beyond the available evidence, particularly through unsupported recovery statements and generalized recommendations.

Potential Impact

Reasoning failures may reduce trust in AI-generated outputs and contribute to downstream decision errors.



Critical Safety Failures

Definition

Failures that have the potential to significantly alter patient understanding or clinical decision-making.

Examples include:

Incorrect medication guidance
Missing emergency instructions
Hallucinated treatment recommendations
Major changes in clinician intent

Observed Benchmark Examples

Critical safety failures were identified whenever generated content introduced or removed clinically meaningful information with the potential to affect downstream communication or patient understanding.

Potential Impact

These failures represent the highest-priority category for future benchmark development because they have the greatest potential to influence safety.



Taxonomy Development

Version 0.1 of this taxonomy emerged through manual analysis of the initial twenty benchmark cases.

Rather than defining categories before evaluation, recurring failure patterns were identified directly from benchmark observations and organized into standardized categories. As additional benchmark cases are evaluated, this taxonomy will continue to evolve through empirical observation rather than theoretical assumptions.
